{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775847152803,"sessionID":"ses_28744045fffezd1wEfQExmvKdi","part":{"id":"prt_d78bc7cd8001w0nDOazu4XAaDU","messageID":"msg_d78bc6bd9001Re1PBBsClV5F6q","sessionID":"ses_28744045fffezd1wEfQExmvKdi","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_637f1d9b5cac4b5bbc973bd7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Proposal: AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心\n\n## Summary\n\nImplement an HTTP reverse proxy core in `pkg/router` to route external HTTP requests to dynamically created sandbox endpoints managed by AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs. This enables external clients to access agent sessions and code interpreter environments through a unified entry point.\n\n## Purpose\n\n### Background\n\nThe AR-007 controller creates sandbox Pods based on AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs. Currently:\n\n- **No external access mechanism**: Sandboxes are isolated within the cluster with no way for external clients to reach them\n- **Manual port forwarding**: Operators must manually set up port forwarding or Ingress for each sandbox\n- **Inconsistent routing**: Each sandbox type requires different access patterns\n- **No unified entry point**: Clients need to manage multiple endpoint addresses\n\n### Goal\n\nProvide a reverse proxy that:\n- Dynamically discovers active sandbox endpoints from AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter status\n- Routes HTTP requests to the appropriate sandbox based on routing rules\n- Supports path-based and header-based routing\n- Manages connection lifecycle and health checking\n- Provides authentication and rate limiting at the proxy level\n\n### Value\n- Simplifies client access to sandbox environments\n- Centralized authentication and security at the proxy layer\n- Dynamic scaling without manual reconfiguration\n- Consistent routing across different sandbox types\n- Enables multi-tenant access control\n\n---\n\n## Scope\n\n### In-Scope\n\n| Deliverable | Description |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| Reverse Proxy Server | Core HTTP server with dynamic backend management |\n| Endpoint Discovery | Watch AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter CRs for active endpoints |\n| Routing Engine | Path-based, header-based, and weighted routing |\n| Health Checker | Periodic health checks for backend endpoints |\n| Connection Pool | Reusable connections to backends with keep-alive |\n| Access Control | Authentication middleware and rate limiting |\n| Metrics | Request latency, error rates, backend health |\n| Unit Tests | Core routing logic coverage >60% |\n\n### Code Structure\n\n```\npkg/router/\n├── server.go                     # HTTP server with proxy logic\n├── router.go                     # Router interface and implementation\n├── discovery/\n│   ├── discovery.go              # Endpoint discovery from CRs\n│   ├── agentruntime_watcher.go   # AgentRuntime endpoint watcher\n│   └── codeinterpreter_watcher.go # CodeInterpreter endpoint watcher\n├── backend/\n│   ├── backend.go                # Backend pool management\n│   ├── healthcheck.go            # Health checking logic\n│   └── connpool.go               # Connection pooling\n├── routing/\n│   ├── router.go                 # Routing rule engine\n│   ├── path_routing.go           # Path-based routing\n│   └── header_routing.go         # Header-based routing\n├── middleware/\n│   ├── auth.go                   # Authentication middleware\n│   ├── ratelimit.go              # Rate limiting\n│   └── logging.go                # Request logging\n├── metrics/\n│   └── metrics.go                # Prometheus metrics\n├── config/\n│   └── config.go                 # Configuration struct\n└── router_test.go                # Unit tests\n```\n\n### Configuration\n\nThe router supports these configuration options:\n\n| Option | Type | Default | Description |\n|--------|------|---------|-------------|\n| listenAddress | string | \":8080\" | Proxy listen address |\n| backendTimeout | duration | 30s | Timeout for backend requests |\n| idleTimeout | duration | 60s | Idle connection timeout |\n| maxConnsPerBackend | int | 100 | Max connections per backend |\n| healthCheckInterval | duration | 10s | Backend health check interval |\n| healthCheckTimeout | duration | 5s | Health check timeout |\n| rateLimitEnabled | bool | false | Enable rate limiting |\n| rateLimitRPS | int | 100 | Requests per second per client |\n| authEnabled | bool | false | Enable authentication |\n| watchNamespaces | []string | all | Namespaces to watch for CRs |\n\n### Out-of-Scope\n- TCP/UDP proxying (HTTP only)\n- TLS termination (handled by Ingress)\n- WebSocket support (future enhancement)\n- Multi-cluster routing (separate module)\n- Custom routing rules CRD (future enhancement)\n\n---\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Dependencies\n\n| Dependency | Source | Purpose |\n|------------|--------|---------|\n| github.com/volcano/sh/agentcube/client-go | local | Kubernetes typed client for CR watch |\n| github.com/volcano/sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1 | local | AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter types |\n| k8s.io/client-go/informers | ^0.34 | Cached list/watch for CRs |\n| k8s.io/client-go/tools/cache | ^0.34 | SharedIndexInformer for CR watching |\n| github.com/gin-gonic/gin | ^1.9 | HTTP server (optional, can use stdlib) |\n| github.com/prometheus/client_golang | ^1.20 | Prometheus metrics |\n\n### Upstream Dependencies\n\n- **AR-007 K8s Reconciler** — Creates sandboxes that the router proxies to\n- **AR-005/AR-006 Sandbox Creation** — Endpoints are discovered from these APIs\n\n### Downstream Consumers\n\n1. **External Clients** — Access agent runtimes and code interpreters through the proxy\n2. **Ingress Controllers** — Can route to the proxy as a backend\n3. **Monitoring** — Proxy metrics for operational visibility\n4. **API Gateway** — Can use the proxy as a transport layer\n\n### Risks\n\n| Risk | Severity | Mitigation |\n|------|----------|------------|\n| Backend not ready | Medium | Health checks, retry with backoff |\n| Proxy becomes bottleneck | Medium | Connection pooling, horizontal scaling |\n| Stale endpoints | Medium | Watch-based discovery with immediate updates |\n| Authentication bypass | High | Middleware validation, default deny |\n| Resource exhaustion | Medium | Connection limits, rate limiting |\n| Routing loops | Low | Backend self-referential checks |\n\n---\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Option 1: Custom Reverse Proxy with CR Watch (Selected)\n\n**Approach**: Implement a custom HTTP reverse proxy that watches AgentRuntime/CodeInterpreter CRs and dynamically updates backend pool.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Full control over routing logic\n- Tight integration with CR status for endpoint discovery\n- Can implement custom health checking\n- Lightweight compared to generic proxies\n\n**Cons**:\n- Additional code to maintain\n- Need to implement connection pooling\n\n**Decision**: Selected — provides the best integration with the existing CR-based workflow and allows custom routing logic.\n\n---\n\n### Option 2: Use NGINX Ingress Controller\n\n**Approach**: Configure NGINX Ingress with Dynamic Configuration or Kubernetes Gateway API.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Mature, production-tested reverse proxy\n- Rich routing features\n- Built-in load balancing\n\n**Cons**:\n- Requires additional CRDs for dynamic backend updates\n- Less visibility into CR status\n- Heavyweight for simple proxy use case\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — adds complexity and external dependency when a simpler solution suffices.\n\n---\n\n### Option 3: Use Envoy Proxy with Control Plane\n\n**Approach**: Deploy Envoy with a custom control plane that programs routes based on CRs.\n\n**Pros**:\n- High-performance proxy\n- Rich feature set\n- Production-tested at scale\n\n**Cons**:\n- Significant complexity in control plane implementation\n- Requires maintaining Envoy configurations\n- Over-engineered for the current scope\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — the complexity outweighs the benefits for the current use case.\n\n---\n\n### Option 4: Use Kubernetes Service with NodePort\n\n**Approach**: Expose each sandbox as a NodePort Service.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Native Kubernetes approach\n- No custom proxy code\n\n**Cons**:\n- Port exhaustion with many sandboxes\n- No path-based routing\n- No unified access point\n- Security concerns with node ports\n\n**Decision**: Rejected — does not provide the required routing capabilities.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### Phase 1: Router Foundation\n- [ ] Create pkg/router module structure\n- [ ] Implement Config with defaults and CLI flags\n- [ ] Create Router interface and basic implementation\n- [ ] Set up HTTP server with graceful shutdown\n\n### Phase 2: Endpoint Discovery\n- [ ] Implement CR watcher for AgentRuntime\n- [ ] Implement CR watcher for CodeInterpreter\n- [ ] Extract endpoint info from CR status\n- [ ] Handle CR add/update/delete events\n\n### Phase 3: Backend Management\n- [ ] Implement backend pool with dynamic updates\n- [ ] Implement connection pooling\n- [ ] Implement health checking with configurable intervals\n- [ ] Handle backend failures and recovery\n\n### Phase 4: Routing Engine\n- [ ] Implement path-based routing\n- [ ] Implement header-based routing\n- [ ] Implement default routing strategy\n- [ ] Add routing rule configuration\n\n### Phase 5: Middleware\n- [ ] Add request logging middleware\n- [ ] Implement rate limiting (token bucket)\n- [ ] Add authentication middleware\n- [ ] Add metrics collection\n\n### Phase 6: Testing\n- [ ] Unit tests for routing logic\n- [ ] Unit tests for backend pool\n- [ ] Mock tests for health checking\n- [ ] Integration tests with mock API server\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Router starts and listens on configured address\n- [ ] Endpoints are discovered from AgentRuntime CRs\n- [ ] Endpoints are discovered from CodeInterpreter CRs\n- [ ] Requests are routed to the correct backend based on path\n- [ ] Requests are routed based on headers when configured\n- [ ] Unhealthy backends are removed from the pool\n- [ ] Connection pooling works correctly\n- [ ] Rate limiting restricts requests when enabled\n- [ ] Authentication middleware validates requests\n- [ ] Metrics are exported for Prometheus\n- [ ] Graceful shutdown terminates existing connections\n- [ ] Unit tests pass with >60% coverage\n- [ ] Router integrates with AR-007 controller for lifecycle","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/proposal.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.\n\nLSP errors detected in other files:\n<diagnostics file=\"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/client/informers/externalversions/runtime/v1alpha1/interface.go\">\nERROR [4:2] \"github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1\" imported and not used\n</diagnostics>\n\nLSP errors detected in other files:\n<diagnostics file=\"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/workloadmanager/reconciler/reconciler_test.go\">\nERROR [146:6] expected '(', found TestGetObservedGenerationCodeInterpreter\n</diagnostics>\n\nLSP errors detected in other files:\n<diagnostics file=\"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/workloadmanager/expiration_test.go\">\nERROR [94:16] undefined: metav1\n</diagnostics>\n\nLSP errors detected in other files:\n<diagnostics file=\"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/pkg/workloadmanager/server_test.go\">\nERROR [15:2] \"k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/watch\" imported and not used\nERROR [66:14] cannot use &metav1.Status{…} (value of type *\"k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1\".Status) as error value in return statement: *\"k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1\".Status does not implement error (missing method Error)\nERROR [81:9] cannot use &metav1.Status{…} (value of type *\"k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/api